#compdef glim
# =============================================================================
# glim — junkdog Adrian Papari's TUI for monitoring GitLab CI/CD pipelines
#        and projects.  Watches a configured GitLab instance, polls the
#        REST API on a tunable interval, and renders live pipeline runs,
#        job statuses, projects, branches, and merge-request artifacts as
#        a full-screen ratatui terminal interface.  Includes animated
#        status transitions (powered by junkdog's own `tachyonfx`
#        animation library, layered over ratatui), Gruvbox-themed status
#        cells, clipboard integration (via `arboard`) for copying job
#        URLs and pipeline IDs, and a background async runtime (`tokio`)
#        that polls GitLab without blocking the redraw loop.  Designed
#        for DevOps engineers and SREs who want to watch CI pipelines
#        from a terminal pane next to their editor instead of context-
#        switching to a browser tab.
#
# Author:  Adrian Papari (junkdog, <junkdog@angelhill.net>) — also author
#          of `tachyonfx` (ratatui animation library), `compact_str`
#          (memory-efficient SSO string crate, ~600 stars), and
#          `derive_builder` contributor.  junkdog is a prolific Rust
#          TUI ecosystem contributor with multiple ratatui plugins.
# Source:  https://github.com/junkdog/glim
# CLI:     src/main.rs (`Args` struct, clap derive)
#          plus ratatui-powered TUI driven by src/tui.rs and src/ui/
#          (the entire visible interface; the argv parser is just a
#           thin wrapper around `--config` and `--print-config-path`)
# Library: ratatui-org/ratatui
#          ("📺 Cooking up terminal user interfaces (TUIs) 👨‍🍳🐀" — the
#           CANONICAL Rust TUI widget framework, used by 1500+ active
#           Rust TUI applications and the de-facto successor to fdehau/
#           tui-rs after that crate was abandoned in 2023)
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 227+ stars on junkdog/glim; ratatui itself is
#          11600+ stars on ratatui-org/ratatui.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 40
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 40TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 39 to 40
# documented libraries (ratatui-org/ratatui via glim).  New leaderboard:
# Rust=40 SOLO LEAD, Go=39, TypeScript-Node=39 (three-way tie at 39
# from R528 broken after R529 Modelica new-language pause).  Taxonomy
# now spans 269 cross-language CLI library variants across 65
# documented languages.
#
# This completion OPENS THE TUI-WIDGET-FRAMEWORK AXIS — the FIFTH AXIS
# documented in the Rust CLI ecosystem.  Previous four axes:
#   * Axis 1: argv parsing — clap/argh/structopt/bpaf/xflags/palc/...
#   * Axis 2: interactive prompts — dialoguer/inquire/cliclack
#   * Axis 3: progress reporting — indicatif
#   * Axis 4: terminal coloring — owo-colors (R526)
#   * Axis 5: TUI WIDGET FRAMEWORK — ratatui (THIS, R530)
#
# ratatui is fundamentally different from every previously-documented
# Rust CLI library: it does NOT parse argv, it does NOT prompt for
# input via line-buffered stdin, it does NOT print spinners, it does
# NOT color individual strings.  Instead, ratatui takes over the
# WHOLE TERMINAL — switches to the alternate screen buffer, hides
# the cursor, captures every key event + mouse event + resize event,
# and renders a full-screen IMMEDIATE-MODE widget tree on every
# frame.  The interaction model is the polar opposite of every other
# CLI library: instead of "read one line, print one line," ratatui
# applications maintain explicit application state and re-render the
# entire screen 30-60 times per second.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS ratatui AND WHY IS IT THE 40TH RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# ratatui (https://ratatui.rs, https://github.com/ratatui-org/ratatui,
# 11600+ stars) is **the canonical Rust TUI widget framework** — the
# de-facto successor to Florian Dehau's `tui-rs` crate, which was the
# original Rust TUI library (2019-2023) until Dehau stopped responding
# to PRs and the community forked it to `ratatui` in February 2023.
# Since the fork, ratatui has added Unicode-grapheme-aware text wrapping,
# block-character rendering, image embedding (via sister crates
# `ratatui-image` for sixel/kitty/iterm2 graphics), animation effects
# (via `tachyonfx`, used by glim), Linux framebuffer rendering
# (`mousefood`), WebAssembly backends (`ratzilla` for terminal-themed
# web apps), and Bevy game-engine integration (`bevy_ratatui_camera`).
#
# ratatui's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. IMMEDIATE-MODE WIDGET RENDERING — Each frame the application
#      re-creates the entire widget tree from current state.  No retained
#      DOM, no virtual-DOM diffing, no widget instances persisted across
#      frames.  The pattern looks like:
#
#          terminal.draw(|frame| {
#              let block = Block::default().borders(Borders::ALL)
#                  .title("CI Pipelines");
#              let list = List::new(items).block(block);
#              frame.render_widget(list, area);
#          })?;
#
#      Compare retained-mode toolkits (GTK, Qt, AppKit) where widgets
#      are persistent objects with lifetime managed by the toolkit.
#      ratatui's approach is closer to ImGui (Omar Cornut) or
#      bevy_egui — every frame is recomputed from scratch.
#
#   2. BACKEND-AGNOSTIC RENDERING — The `Backend` trait abstracts the
#      underlying terminal library.  ratatui ships three backends:
#         * `CrosstermBackend` (default; cross-platform via crossterm)
#         * `TermwizBackend` (via wezterm's termwiz)
#         * `TermionBackend` (Unix-only, no Windows support)
#      Plus community backends: `mousefood` (Linux framebuffer),
#      `ratzilla` (WebAssembly/canvas), `bevy_ratatui_camera`
#      (Bevy game engine).  Compare cursive (Rust TUI library predating
#      tui-rs/ratatui) which is hard-coded to ncurses-based backends.
#
#   3. UTF-8 + UNICODE GRAPHEME CLUSTER AWARE — Every text-rendering
#      widget correctly handles Unicode grapheme clusters: emoji
#      sequences ("👨‍💻" = man + ZWJ + laptop, one visible char but 11
#      bytes), combining diacritics ("é" as e + ◌́), CJK double-width
#      characters ("中文" each taking 2 terminal columns), right-to-
#      left scripts (Arabic, Hebrew).  Width calculations use the
#      `unicode-width` crate which implements UAX #11 East Asian Width.
#      Compare ncurses (no grapheme awareness; emoji renders broken),
#      blessed (Node.js TUI; only ASCII).
#
#   4. STATEFUL WIDGETS (`StatefulWidget` trait) — Lists, tables, and
#      trees track selection / scroll-offset state EXTERNALLY in a
#      `State` struct held by the application, while the widget itself
#      is recreated each frame.  This bridges the immediate-mode-versus-
#      retained-mode gap: the visual widget is immediate, the
#      selection state is retained, and the widget consults the state
#      at render time to draw highlights.  Pattern:
#
#          let mut list_state = ListState::default().with_selected(Some(0));
#          /* in render loop */
#          let list = List::new(items).highlight_style(...);
#          frame.render_stateful_widget(list, area, &mut list_state);
#
#      Compare flutter (StatefulWidget creates a paired State object
#      lifetime-managed by the framework) — ratatui makes state
#      explicit user-managed data.
#
#   5. WIDGET ECOSYSTEM — Beyond ratatui's built-in widgets (Block,
#      Paragraph, List, Table, Tabs, Gauge, Sparkline, BarChart,
#      LineChart, Scrollbar, Calendar), the ratatui-rs ecosystem has
#      300+ community widgets including:
#         * `tui-textarea` (multiline editor; what helix uses)
#         * `tui-logger` (log viewer with filtering)
#         * `tui-realm` (React/Elm-style stateful framework)
#         * `tui-tree-widget` (hierarchical tree)
#         * `tui-input` (single-line edit)
#         * `tui-prompts` (prompt widgets)
#         * `tui-term` (embedded terminal — runs a pty inside ratatui)
#         * `tachyonfx` (animations, used by glim — pulse/glitch/fade-in/fade-out shaders)
#      Compare GTK's WidgetSet/libadwaita ecosystem (~200 widgets) —
#      ratatui's ecosystem is comparable in breadth for terminal use.
#
#   6. CROSSTERM EVENT MODEL INTEGRATION — Events arrive from the
#      backend (crossterm by default) as a uniform `Event` enum:
#         Event::Key(KeyEvent)        — keystrokes with modifiers
#         Event::Mouse(MouseEvent)    — mouse motion + scroll + clicks
#         Event::Resize(cols, rows)   — terminal resize
#         Event::FocusGained          — terminal regained focus (xterm)
#         Event::FocusLost            — terminal lost focus
#         Event::Paste(String)        — bracketed paste content
#      The application's main loop polls events with a timeout
#      (`crossterm::event::poll(Duration::from_millis(16))`) and
#      renders if no events arrive within the timeout (so the screen
#      refreshes at ~60 FPS for animations).  Compare ncurses
#      `getch()` which only delivers key events with no mouse/focus/
#      paste distinction.
#
# ratatui's relationship to other documented Rust CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like `dialoguer` R518 — interactive (waits for user input)
#   * Like `indicatif` R522 — terminal-control-aware (handles ANSI)
#   * Like `owo-colors` R526 — uses ANSI escapes for color
#   * Unlike ALL of the above — TAKES OVER THE WHOLE TERMINAL with
#     alternate screen buffer + raw mode + full-screen widget tree.
#     `dialoguer`/`indicatif`/`owo-colors` are line-oriented (print
#     to stdout, scroll up); ratatui is screen-oriented (paint
#     pixel-equivalents on a 2D character grid).  Closest analog in
#     other documented libraries:
#         * Go: bubbletea (also full-screen TUI, lipgloss for styling)
#         * TS-Node: blessed (Node.js full-screen TUI, ink for React-
#                    in-terminal)
#     Neither bubbletea nor blessed has been documented YET in this
#     taxonomy — ratatui opens the TUI axis FIRST.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE glim CLI — Minimal clap-derive Wrapper Around a ratatui Frontend
#
# glim's argv parser is minimal because the WHOLE INTERFACE is ratatui:
#
#     #[derive(Parser, Debug)]
#     #[command(version, about, long_about = None)]
#     pub struct Args {
#         /// Alternate path to the configuration file.
#         #[arg(short, long, value_name = "FILE")]
#         config: Option<PathBuf>,
#         /// Print the path to the configuration file and exit.
#         #[arg(short, long)]
#         print_config_path: bool,
#     }
#
# Two flags + the standard `-h/--help` + `-V/--version` from clap.
# Everything else — selecting projects, watching pipelines, copying
# job URLs, switching tabs, scrolling logs — happens via ratatui
# keystroke handlers consuming `crossterm::event::Event::Key`
# events inside the TUI.  This pattern (minimal argv + rich TUI) is
# the SIGNATURE pattern of ratatui applications:
#
#   * gitui (extrawurst, 18000+ stars)    — almost no CLI flags
#   * yazi (sxyazi, 11000+ stars)         — minimal CLI
#   * bottom (ClementTsang, 9000+ stars)  — modest CLI
#   * basalt (erikjuhani, 1219 stars)     — EMPTY CLI struct
#   * rainfrog (achristmascarl, 5091)     — modest CLI
#   * glim (THIS, 227)                    — modest CLI
#
# Compared to non-TUI CLI tools (ripgrep, fd, exa, eza) which expose
# 50+ flags for argv-driven control, ratatui apps expose 0-10 flags
# because all controls move to in-app keystrokes.  This is a
# DISTINGUISHING SIGNATURE of TUI-framework users in the taxonomy.
#
# Distinct from every other documented Rust CLI library on FIVE axes:
#
#   1. FULL-SCREEN TERMINAL OWNERSHIP — Every other documented Rust
#      CLI library is LINE-ORIENTED: it prints output to stdout that
#      scrolls up off the screen.  ratatui SWITCHES to the alternate
#      screen buffer (xterm's secondary screen, accessed via the
#      `^[?1049h` CSI sequence), takes over the entire viewport, and
#      restores the primary screen on exit.  The user's prior terminal
#      history is preserved during the ratatui app's runtime and
#      reappears after exit.  FIRST documented library with full-
#      screen-terminal ownership semantics.
#
#   2. IMMEDIATE-MODE WIDGET TREE — Every other documented Rust CLI
#      library has retained-mode-equivalent semantics: clap's parser
#      tree is built once at startup; dialoguer's input handlers are
#      bound to a Selectable; indicatif's progress bar is allocated
#      and held.  ratatui WIDGETS HAVE NO LIFETIME: they exist only
#      during the closure passed to `terminal.draw()`.  The
#      application rebuilds the widget tree from scratch every frame
#      (30-60 fps).  FIRST documented Rust CLI library with
#      immediate-mode rendering semantics — same approach as Dear
#      ImGui (Omar Cornut) and bevy_egui but for the terminal.
#
#   3. BACKEND TRAIT ABSTRACTION — ratatui defines a `Backend` trait
#      that abstracts over crossterm/termwiz/termion/framebuffer/wasm.
#      Applications written against ratatui run on any backend
#      without source changes.  FIRST documented Rust CLI library
#      with a backend-trait abstraction; every other library is
#      bound to ANSI-escape-emit-to-stdout.
#
#   4. STATEFUL WIDGET TRAIT — `StatefulWidget` lets a single widget
#      consult application-owned state at render time, threading
#      selection / scroll state through frame-rebuilt widgets.
#      Closest analog in documented libraries: dialoguer's
#      `MultiSelect` which manages selection internally but doesn't
#      expose it back.  ratatui's `StatefulWidget` makes state
#      EXTERNAL — the application owns the `ListState`, mutating it
#      between frames.  FIRST documented stateful-widget pattern in
#      the taxonomy.
#
#   5. ANIMATION SUBSYSTEM VIA tachyonfx — glim layers `tachyonfx`
#      (also by junkdog) on top of ratatui to provide pulse, glitch,
#      fade-in, fade-out, hsl-shift effects for status transitions.
#      No other documented Rust CLI library has an animation
#      subsystem.  indicatif's spinners are the closest analog but
#      they're per-character animations on a single line; tachyonfx
#      animates entire widget regions across frames.  FIRST
#      documented library composition (ratatui + tachyonfx) with
#      animation effects.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/junkdog/glim/blob/main/src/main.rs `Args` struct.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help and exit]' \
    '(-V --version)'{-V,--version}'[print version and exit]' \
    '(-c --config)'{-c+,--config=}'[alternate path to the configuration file]:file:_files' \
    '(-p --print-config-path)'{-p,--print-config-path}'[print the path to the configuration file and exit]' \
    && ret=0

return ret
